<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BUTCHER: SHOULDER CUT TRIMS BILL AT MEAT COUNTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MERLE ELLIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If you want to save money at the meat counter, you must get to know "chuck." 
Chuck is not the name of any particular friendly and generous butcher. It is 
rather the name of a large part of a beef carcass. For some reason unknown to 
me, the front shoulder of the beef animal is called the chuck. Every other 
animal in the world has shoulders -- lambs have shoulders, veal have shoulders, 
pigs have shoulders. Beef have, instead, chucks. 
</P>
<P>
The chuck makes up about 26% of the total carcass weight and, for the most 
part, has been considered a less-tender part of the animal that generally 
requires long-slow-moist-heat cooking. That there is a lot of it and that it is 
generally considered tough and less desirable have made the chuck a problem for 
the beef industry for years. 
</P>
<P>
Butchers have traditionally had to discount the chuck in order to move it. That 
has made it a good value for consumers throughout the years. If you have, as 
grandmother seemed to, plenty of time to make stews and pot roasts using 
long-slow-moist-heat cooking, the chuck is a cut that can save plenty of money 
on meals. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Well-Rounded Chuck 
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, according to a recent study conducted at South Dakota State 
University, you might not even need much time to save a lot of money with 
chuck. Some chuck muscles from today's leaner younger beef cattle, it was 
found, are tender enough to do all kinds of things with besides pot roast. 
</P>
<P>
The research was funded by the Beef Industry Council, the South Dakota Beef 
Council and the California Beef Council for the purpose of discovering if the 
chuck might not have potentially greater value if sold as individual cuts 
rather than as one cut with several muscles. The result of the study was 
reported in the Journal of Food Science. 
</P>
<P>
Scientists studied the eating characteristics of 34 muscles/muscle groups 
within the forequarters of 16 Angus steers of similar genetic and nutritional 
background. They determined the fat and lean content of each, as well as the 
chemical characteristics of the connective tissue, the component largely 
responsible for the chuck being less tender. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
What's in It for You? 
</P>
<P>
What the research indicated was that if the beef industry could develop 
fabrication and processing techniques to allow easy and cost-effective 
separation of the muscles of the chuck, its value could be significantly 
increased. 
</P>
<P>
So what does this mean to you? Two things. First, you can be sure that the beef 
industry is going to be working overtime to find ways of taking the chuck apart 
so the parts can be sold to you for more money. And second, if you're willing 
to do a little cutting-up in the kitchen, you can take a chuck apart yourself 
and do all kinds of wonderful things with the meat. You don't have to be a 
scientist -- or even a butcher -- to take a chuck apart, and the results can be 
surprisingly rewarding both in terms of good food and money saved. 
</P>
<P>
After reading about the South Dakota study, I decided to do my own. I went to 
the market and picked up a three-pound piece of boneless chuck roast. I would 
like to have found one with the bone in, they are always a better buy, but 
those are getting harder and harder to find. They must have found some way to 
cross those critters with jellyfish; they don't have any bones anymore. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
The Lean Is Left 
</P>
<P>
At home, I took it apart. It was more a matter of simply pulling it apart 
rather than any skilled knife work. The individual muscles are separated by 
connective tissue and they come apart rather easily. Then, by carefully 
trimming away all fat and silvery connective tissue, you are left with several 
pieces, some large and some small, of solid lean meat. 
</P>
<P>
I don't know the names of the muscles that I cut from my chuck. I don't know 
which, if any, was the Brachiocephalicus or the Longissimus dorsi or the 
Triceps brachi. But it was not difficult to tell, even without cooking, which 
were the more tender. Those with a finer texture, some almost like velvet, are 
apt to be more tender than the muscles with a coarse stringy look to them. 
</P>
<P>
Try this quick beef stew Italiano. It takes less than 30 minutes and tastes 
like you cooked it all day. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
STIR-FRY STEW ITALIANO 
</P>
<P>
1/2 pound well-trimmed boneless chuck meat 
</P>
<P>
2 cloves garlic, minced 
</P>
<P>
5 teaspoons olive oil 
</P>
<P>
1 medium onion, sliced 
</P>
<P>
1 medium zucchini, sliced 
</P>
<P>
2 teaspoons flour 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon dried basil leaves 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
1/8 teaspoon crushed red pepper pods 
</P>
<P>
2 medium tomatoes, seeded and chopped 
</P>
<P>
1/3 cup white wine 
</P>
<P>
Polenta wedges, optional 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon grated Parmesan cheese 
</P>
<P>
Cut boneless chuck into 1/4-inch thick strips. Cut each strip into about 1 inch 
pieces. Using side of cook's knife, mash garlic cloves to form paste. Combine 
garlic with 2 teaspoons olive oil and add to beef strips in small bowl, 
stirring to combine. Set aside. 
</P>
<P>
Saute sliced onion in 2 teaspoons olive oil in large skillet 3 minutes. 
(Good-sized black iron skillet with lid is preferred.) 
</P>
<P>
Add beef and garlic and cook, stirring, 2 minutes. Add sliced zucchini and 
continue cooking 1 to 2 minutes. Sprinkle flour, basil, salt and red pepper 
over meat and vegetables. Stir in and cook another minute. 
</P>
<P>
Add tomatoes and wine. Cover and simmer 4 or 5 minutes, just until sauce 
thickens slightly. Serve over wedge of polenta. Sprinkle stew with grated 
Parmesan cheese. Makes 4 servings.a 
</P>
<P>
Note: Neva's Quick Polenta, slices of fried commercial cornmeal mush, may be 
substituted for regular polenta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Chuck roast is easily separated into three individual muscles. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
